Narrative: An unoccupied Zoox autonomous vehicle (Vehicle 1) was traveling east on Alameda Street near Bryant Street in San Francisco. It began to slow down for a stopped box truck (Vehicle 2) in the same lane, which had an open liftgate. As the Zoox vehicle was preparing to maneuver around, Vehicle 2 began to reverse. The Zoox vehicle came to a stop however, Vehicle 2 continued reversing. The Zoox vehicle honked, but Vehicle 2's open liftgate made contact with the right front fender and front fascia of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle was towed from the scene and was found to have sustained minor damage. The police were notified, and no injuries were reported.

Narrative: An unoccupied Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) was stationary in the right lane on northeast-bound Bryant Street at 6th Street in San Francisco, stopped behind traffic at a red light. After the light turned green, the Zoox vehicle initially remained stopped to yield to an active police vehicle making a right turn onto 6th Street from the adjacent lane. During the subsequent green light cycle, as the Zoox vehicle began to proceed straight along Bryant Street, two passenger cars, including  Vehicle 2, cut across its path from behind, attempting an illegal right turn onto 6th Street from a through lane. The Zoox vehicle braked hard, but contact was unavoidable, and Vehicle 2 clipped the Zoox vehicle's left front fender. The front-seat passenger of Vehicle 2 exited to inspect the Zoox vehicle before returning to their car and leaving the scene without exchanging information. The Zoox vehicle then cleared the scene and returned to base. Upon inspection, the Zoox vehicle was found to have sustained minor damage. Police were notified, and no injuries were reported.

Narrative:
On December 21, 2025 at 1:17 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a van on Blackburn Avenue near La Cienega Boulevard.
The Waymo AV was stopped facing west on Blackburn Avenue for a red light at the intersection with La Cienega Boulevard with its right turn signal activated. After remaining stopped for approximately six minutes a short distance in advance of the stop line at the red light, the Waymo AV passenger opened the rear left side door and exited the vehicle, and a van that was initially stopped directly behind the Waymo AV maneuvered to the left before slowing to a stop behind the Waymo AV. The Waymo AV passenger briefly interacted with the van operator through the van window, and then re-entered the Waymo AV. The van then proceeded to pass the Waymo AV on the left and the right side of the van made contact with the rear left side of the stationary Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage. The passenger in the Waymo AV was not belted at the time of the collision.

Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Narrative: The May Mobility vehicle (Ego) was operating in autonomy while waiting in slow traffic in the leftmost of two parallel lanes. Ahead, both lanes were obstructed by stopped vehicles, prompting traffic to move to the center turn lane to proceed. The Autonomous Vehicle Operator (AVO) intervened to move closer to the lead vehicle as another vehicle in the right lane attempted to merge left, preventing it. After the merging car stopped, the AVO pulled closer to the lead vehicle, removing any space to merge. As the lead vehicle began to move, both the AVO and the vehicle to the right immediately accelerated, while the merging vehicle moved left into the side of the May AV. Had the Ego remained in Autonomous mode, it would have maintained a safe distance allowing the merging vehicle to proceed safely. No software defects led to this event. This behavior goes against the training of May AVOs. Upon review of this AVOs actions it was decided to remove this person from their role as an AVO.

Narrative: The May Mobility vehicle (Ego) is stopped at a red light, then the Ego begins to accelerate and turn right when the traffic light changes to green. As the Ego accelerates, a pedestrian begins moving and enters the crosswalk from the other side of the intersection. This activates the rule-based crosswalk logic. Ego determines that it is able to stop before the crosswalk without exceeding our max deceleration threshold, which triggers an in-policy stopping reaction for the crosswalk. The Ego brakes to yield for the pedestrian. The vehicle trailing the Ego accelerates, making contact with the rear-end of the Ego. In the 2.5 seconds between the start of the Ego braking and the collision, the rear vehicle accelerated from 0.2 to 6.1 m/s (0.4 to 13.6 mph) without slowing until after the collision occurred. In response to this incident, immediate mitigations were made, in that the vehicle operators (AVOs) operate all intersections in manual mode.  This remained in place until January 12, when we received a solution which instituted a reduction of the 3.5 m/s2 parameter, in order to prevent the Ego from yielding to pedestrians in crosswalks that are still far from the Egos lane if such yielding would induce braking.

Narrative: The May Mobility vehicle (Ego) approaches a turn with a trailing vehicle following closely behind. The May planner initially selects a trajectory it believes will safely complete the turn. However, as the Ego begins the turn, it re-evaluates the situation and detects a significant risk of striking the curb. At that point, the planner shifts focus from avoiding the curb entirely to minimizing the severity of a potential curb strike. To reduce speed before the expected contact, the Ego brakes at 3.5 m/s). Because the trailing vehicle is following so closely, this deceleration makes a rear-end collision likely. The Ego predicts a potential rear-end collision and elects to reduce brake force to lessen the impact severity. Moments later, the trailing vehicle strikes the rear driver-side bumper of the Ego and then drives away. Future improvements are underway to give the planner a policy option to steer away from curbs. This new capability will help the vehicle avoid situations where braking becomes the only remaining way to manage close curb proximity.

Narrative:
On December 13, 2025 at 1:35 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on W. 3rd Street near S. Western Avenue. 
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on W. 3rd Street in the left lane and proceeding straight at the intersection at S. Western Avenue. While the Waymo AV was exiting the intersection, a passenger car traveling southbound on S. Western Avenue proceeded to make a right turn onto W. 3rd Street. As the passenger car was completing the right turn, the passenger car partially entered the Waymo AV's lane of travel, and the front left side of the passenger car made contact with the rear right side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage. The driver of the passenger car alleged a minor injury.

Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Narrative:
On December 12, 2025 at 8:26 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Palo Alto, California was in a collision involving a cyclist on W. Middlefield Road at San Antonio Road.
The Waymo AV was traveling northwestbound in the rightmost lane on W. Middlefield Road with its right turn signal activated and preparing to make a right turn at a green light onto San Antonio Road. As the Waymo AV began initiating the right turn, the Waymo AV came to a stop within the crosswalk to yield to a cyclist. The cyclist was traveling southbound on the east sidewalk of San Antonio Road and entered the crosswalk across W. Middlefield Road against a red pedestrian crosswalk light. As the cyclist entered the crosswalk, the front tire of the bicycle made contact with the right side of the stationary Waymo AV and the cyclist fell to the ground. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The cyclist was transported to a hospital in an ambulance.

Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because an individual involved was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Narrative: During normal autonomous operation, the May autonomous shuttle (Ego) was traveling through a narrow section of roadway in a parking lot bordered by parked vehicles on the left and a retaining wall on the right on experimental software version v29.0.20. As the Ego proceeded, the system initially recognized the static retaining wall as a large, non-rectangular object. As the Ego approaches the wall, the resulting density of lidar returns on the object (wall) exceeds the detectors maximum limitation. The newer lidar points, toward the forward edge of the elongated object, exceeding the limit were filtered out, causing the track to disappear when the ego approached 5m from the track (i.e. the wall). The situation was exacerbated by the fact that the road edge was incorrectly marked in that section.  The road edge was drawn through the retaining wall and thus the vehicle did not have any prior knowledge about the edge of the road. As a result, the Ego drove too close to the wall, scraping it at a speed of 2 meters per second while driving straight (i.e. in lane-nominal policy) with no nudge or veer corrections. There was no damage to the wall. The limitation leading to the lost track affects Software versions v26.0 (when the Open World Tracklet v2 feature was introduced) through v31.0. This is the only known instance of this failure mode, and in v32.0 an optimization was made to remove the LIDAR threshold entirely and mitigate the vulnerability.  Furthermore, the incorrect road edge annotation was corrected shortly after this incident and the map updated for the deployed vehicles.

Narrative:
The May vehicle was travelling in an autonomous vehicle (AV) only lane approaching an intersection.  A vehicle travelling to the left of the May shuttle (ego) in the non-AV lane performed a right hand turn across the May vehicles path.  Given the full stopping power and the limited space with which the ego had to stop, the ego was physically unable to stop in time before impact.  The primary factor that led to this collision was human error on the part of the other vehicle that was required to yield to through traffic in the AV lane but did not.  Right turns across a straight lane are uncommon, and drivers are typically not used to them, however there are several signs that instruct other traffic to yield to the vehicles in the AV lane.  There were no autonomy faults or errors which led to this incident.
Update:
There was no indication of injury or request for medical attention at the scene. The police report states "Driver 1 complained of neck pain." For this reason, we are updating the highest severity injury alleged field to reflect the minor w/o hospitalization injury level. The remaining content of this report is unchanged from the initial report submitted on September 11, 2025, Report ID #30413-11593-1.

On October 29, 2025, at approximately 2:30 PM PT, a Motional AV with VIN PFDKB4AE3RF000062 was operating in autonomous mode in Las Vegas, Nevada, with a safety driver in the drivers seat. The vehicle was traveling northbound on Las Vegas Boulevard in the second of four lanes from the left, approaching the intersection with Charleston Boulevard.
 
While stopped at a red traffic signal, an adult male pedestrian began crossing Las Vegas Boulevard from the west side of the street, several hundred feet away from a designated crosswalk. The pedestrian proceeded southbound across multiple lanes and paused on a median located ahead and to the left of the AV. The AV detected and classified the pedestrian the entire time.
 
When the traffic signal turned green, the pedestrian remained stopped on the median. Given that the pedestrian remained stopped in place, the AV began to move forward slowly at approximately 2.5 mph and continued to correctly detect and classify the pedestrian. The pedestrian, holding what appears to be an item in a plastic bag, suddenly stepped into the far-left turn lane ahead of the AV, the AV immediately came to a complete stop still in the second  lane. The pedestrian continued crossing, making a light physical contact with the rear drivers side of the vehicle before continuing across the remaining three lanes of traffic still outside of the crosswalk.
 
The vehicle operator then disengaged the autonomous system and pulled over to complete an incident report. No police were notified. There were no injuries, no damage, and no airbag deployments. The pedestrian did not stop at the scene and the identity of the pedestrian is unknown.

Narrative:
The Ohmio Lift was driving on Gemende Drive towards Airport Drive in Riverside California. A minivan reversed out of a parking position (perpendicular parking to road lane) from the right side of the road into the shuttles path and struck the shuttle from the side.
After the incident a supervisor from the Riverside Transport Agency RTA (operator or the vehicle) was called to the side. The RTA supervisor recorded the incident according to RTAs protocols.
In addition to the Ohmio trainer/supervisor being on the vehicle additional Ohmio personal was called to the side as well.

Summary of Events:
-Upon detecting the minivan in the side envelope, the system issued a brake command within 5ms.
-Brake pressure began rising 58ms after the command and exceeded 90% of the requested pressure 164ms after the initial command.
-The minivan reversed out of a parking space perpendicular to the Ohmio Lifts direction of travel and struck the Lift on the side.
-The minivan continued reversing until contact occurred.
-The elapsed time from first detection of the minivan in the side envelope to impact was approximately 358ms.
-The vehicle came to a complete stop in 1.178 seconds.

In Summary:
The other car pushing out from the parking position did not give way as would have been required.
The Ohmio Lift detected the other car getting into the right side of its safety envelope just 358ms before the impact. The reaction time of the Ohmio Lift was as expected in terms of reacting to the signal and initiating a brake maneuver. However, the short time and distance between the other car entering the Ohmio Lift safety envelope (and consequently its track) was too short to avoid the collision. Even if the Ohmio Lift had come to a complete stop before the actual impact the collision would most likely have happened but potentially at a slightly different position.

Narrative:
On August [XXX], 2025, a Beep-operated Ford E-Transit (002B) equipped with an automated driving system developed by Oxa Autonomy Ltd. was involved in a collision with a stationary object in Jacksonville, FL.
While navigating westbound on [XXX] along a predefined route, vehicle 002B began to slowly veer towards the right curb. The vehicle eventually climbed the curb with the right front and rear wheels and the passenger-side mirror contacted a stationary light pole.
There was one passenger onboard at the time of the incident, an employee of the Jacksonville Transportation Authority. There were no reported injuries, and the vehicle was driven from the scene.
Review of the automated driving system logs as well as onboard video footage determined that the operator disengaged the automated driving system 7.5 seconds prior to the vehicle mounting the curb. Further examination of the onboard video footage noted that the operator appeared to be drowsy and inattentive prior to the incident.
Beep confirmed that the operators shift was in compliance with anti-fatigue policies for this operation. The operator was referred for a post-accident drug and alcohol testing following the incident and tested negative for any impairment. Following the conclusion of the investigation into this incident, the operator was separated from employment.

Narrative: The May autonomous vehicle was travelling in an autonomous vehicle (AV) only lane, on [XXX], approaching the intersection at [XXX]  A vehicle travelling to the left of the May shuttle in the non-AV lane attempted to perform a right hand turn across the May vehicles path and collided with the May AV.  The primary factor that led to this collision was human error on the part of the other vehicle that was required to yield to through traffic in the AV lane but did not.  Right turns across a straight lane are uncommon, and drivers are typically not used to them, however there is a metal street sign that instructs other traffic to yield to the vehicles in the AV lane.  There were no autonomy faults or errors which led to this incident.  Additionally, there is a second traffic light at this intersection that warns public drivers to yield to the AV shuttle. This light was not operating as it should during this incident. We are working with our partner to maintain the operation of this light and have implemented a mitigation policy of daily inspections of this light and implementing an AVO in service if this light is not functioning.

Narrative: While traveling north on [XXX], the Autonomous Vehicle Operator (AVO) engages autonomy 3.0 m before the planned right turn and 7.7 m before the break in the curb while traveling at 8.0 m/s.  The May Autonomous Vehicle (ego) was planning to make a tight right turn into a parking lot, which the AVO was unaware of when engaging autonomy.  The ego jerked to the right upon entering autonomy, hitting a curb and damaging both passenger-side front and rear tires and the right rear tire rim.  The AV attempted the right turn despite not having time to slow sufficiently and mounted the curb.  The AVO intervened by accelerating and steering back to the left upon striking the curb, manually maneuvering back to the street while striking a second curb on the opposite side of the parking lot driveway.  Resimulations without the manual intervention show the ego slowing appropriately and making the right turn into the parking lot.  The AVO should have been attentive to the planned route before engaging autonomy.  As a result of this incident, planned improvements to the AVOs instructive dash and audio alerts for upcoming turns have begun to be implemented.

Narrative:
On June [XXX], 2025, a Beep-operated Ford E-Transit (004D) equipped with an automated driving system developed by Oxa Autonomy Ltd. was involved in a collision with a third-party vehicle in Jacksonville, FL. 
While navigating northbound on [XXX], vehicle 004D approached the intersection of [XXX] under automated control. As vehicle 004D proceeded through the intersection, a 2020 Nissan Pathfinder navigating eastbound on [XXX] entered the intersection and struck vehicle 004D on the drivers door. Vehicle 004D had right of way through the intersection with no stop or yield the other vehicle had been stopped at a stop sign prior to the collision. There were no injuries reported at the scene, and both vehicles were driven away from the site of the collision. 
Prior to the collision, the safety operator in vehicle 004D stated that they noticed the other vehicle entering the intersection, applied the vehicles brakes, and steered away from the path of the other vehicle. Though they were able to bring vehicle 004D to a complete stop, they were unable to completely avoid the collision. Review of dashcam footage and of CCTV footage covering the intersection corroborate this narrative. The safety operator was referred for a post-accident drug and alcohol testing after the incident. They tested negative for any impairment. 
Analysis of the ADS logs determined that the ADS had detected the potential collision and had planned an emergency braking action. The safety operators intervention revoked control of the vehicle from the ADS preventing any automated braking actions. 
The [XXX] responded to the accident scene. The driver of the other vehicle was cited for failing to stop at the stop sign, and the JSO CSO noted that vehicle 004D was not at fault for the accident.
